{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 11:27:59.335675", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — SDN spine–leaf lab\\nSummary\\n- Overall: Local host connectivity on each leaf is healthy; cross-leaf (east–west) L2 connectivity is broken.\\n- Impact: host_1_1 ↔ host_1_2 OK; any host on leaf_1 cannot reach hosts on leaf_2 (and vice versa).\\n- Localization: The problem is localized to the OVS datapath/bridges on the switches (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1). Inter-switch L2 forwarding appears impaired (asymmetric/unidirectional counters).\\n- Likely root cause: OVS bridge/datapath is DOWN / not forwarding between switch ports (OVS service or datapath failure or misconfiguration), so inter-leaf L2 forwarding is not occurring. Management interfaces (20.0.0.0/24) and host IP configs are present.\\n\\nKey observations (raw evidence)\\n1) Reachability (ping)\\n- host_1_1 -> host_1_2: 4/4 received, 0% loss, rtt avg ~1.37 ms (functional intra-leaf connectivity).\\n- All cross-leaf pings (any host on leaf_1 -> any host on leaf_2 and vice versa) show 100% loss and the ping output shows immediate \"Destination Host Unreachable\" (ICMP unreachable returned locally), not just timeouts.\\n\\nRepresentative ping outputs:\\n- host_1_1 -> host_1_2: ok (rtt avg 1.374 ms).\\n- host_1_1 -> host_2_1: 4 transmitted, 0 received, +4 errors, 100% packet loss; \"From 10.0.0.1 icmp_seq=1 Destination Host Unreachable\".\\n\\n2) Host network config\\n- All hosts have correct 10.0.0.0/24 addresses and kernel route entries on eth0 (e.g., host_1_1: inet 10.0.0.1/24).\\n- Hosts on leaf_2 show TX counters (they transmitted packets) but RX counters remain 0 for their eth0 (they are not receiving replies).\\n\\n3) Switch/bridge interface and counters (most relevant interfaces shown)\\n- leaf_1:\\n  - eth0 (host_1_1) RX 28 TX 28 — host traffic present.\\n  - eth1 (host_1_2) RX 28 TX 28 — host traffic present.\\n  - eth2 (to spine): RX 0 bytes, TX 31 bytes.\\n  - eth3 (mgmt): inet 20.0.0.2, RX 265 TX 93 (management active).\\n  - ovs-system: state DOWN; logical bridge leaf_1 state DOWN (ovs-system & logical bridge down).\\n- leaf_2:\\n  - eth0 (host_2_1) RX 24 TX 0 (host sent?).\\n  - eth1 (host_2_2) RX 21 TX 0.\\n  - eth2 (to spine): RX 31 bytes, TX 0 bytes.\\n  - eth3 (mgmt): inet 20.0.0.3, RX 327 TX 40 (management active).\\n  - ovs-system: state DOWN; logical bridge leaf_2 state DOWN.\\n- spine_1:\\n  - eth0 (to leaf_1): RX 31 TX 0.\\n  - eth1 (to leaf_2): RX 0 TX 31.\\n  - eth2 (mgmt): inet 20.0.0.1, RX 282 TX 94 (management active).\\n  - ovs-system: state DOWN; logical bridge spine_1 state DOWN.\\n\\nInterpretation of interface counters / asymmetry\\n- leaf_1 eth2 shows TX=31, RX=0 while spine_1 eth0 shows RX=31, TX=0 — traffic from leaf_1 → spine_1 is being received on spine eth0, but spine is not sending back toward leaf_1 on that link.\\n- spine_1 eth1 shows TX=31, RX=0 while leaf_2 eth2 shows RX=31, TX=0 — spine → leaf_2 traffic is being transmitted and received, but leaf_2 → spine reception on that port is 0.\\n- This pattern indicates uni-directional transfers on the inter-switch links and/or the switching fabric (OVS) is not forwarding frames symmetrically between ports.\\n\\nAnomalies / symptoms\\n- OVS bridge/datapath state: ovs-system and the logical OVS bridge on each switch are reported DOWN (from the switch net-config outputs). Despite physical interfaces being UP and assigned to ovs-system as master, the bridge/datapath appears non-functional.\\n- Inter-leaf L2 forwarding failure: Broadcasts/ARP and unicast frames for hosts across leaves do not complete; hosts see no ARP replies and pings fail with \"Destination Host Unreachable\".\\n- Management plane remains up: eth3 on all switches and spine have 20.0.0.x addresses and counters are active — controller reachability over management plane might still be possible (not explicitly tested here).\\n\\nFault localization\\n- Affected components: OVS datapath/bridges on leaf_1, leaf_2, and spine_1.\\n- The break appears in the data-plane path between leaves (the spine and leaf OVS bridges), not at the host NIC configuration — hosts have correct IPs and local routes.\\n- Because all three switches show OVS bridge(s) DOWN, the issue is likely at the switch datapath/service layer (per-switch OVS problem) rather than a single physical link.\\n\\nLikely root cause(s)\\n- Primary likely cause: Open vSwitch datapath/bridge is down or unresponsive on the involved switches (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1). This prevents normal L2 forwarding between host-facing ports on different leaves.\\n  - Evidence: ovs-system state = DOWN and logical bridge state = DOWN on all switches, combined with asymmetric interface counters and complete failure of inter-leaf pings.\\n- Secondary possibilities (less likely from current evidence but consistent with symptoms):\\n  - OVS service (ovs-vswitchd/ovsdb) crashed, failed to create datapath, or is not bound to kernel datapath.\\n  - Controller flows are missing only because ovs is down (controller connectivity may be intact via mgmt network).\\n  - Mis-configuration of bridge ports or VLANs that isolates leaves (but the symmetric down-state across devices points to OVS operational failure rather than a single ACL/VLAN misconfiguration).\\n\\nAdditional supporting notes\\n- Intra-leaf traffic works (hosts on the same leaf can ping each other) — this implies local host-to-host bridging or direct L2 path on that leaf is functional enough for intra-leaf, but inter-switch bridging is failing.\\n- Management interfaces (20.0.0.x) show activity and valid addresses on switches. Controller reachability should be verified separately; if controller is reachable, OVS being DOWN would still prevent flows from being installed.\\n\\nRecommended next diagnostic checks (no remediation steps here)\\n- Check OVS daemon/process status on leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1 (systemctl status ovs-vswitchd / ovsdb-server) and check their logs for errors.\\n- Run ovs-vsctl show / ovs-ofctl show on each switch to confirm bridge/datapath state and whether ports are present.\\n- Confirm controller connectivity from each switch (e.g., ping 20.0.0.100, check controller connection in ovs-vsctl or ovs-ofctl).\\n- Inspect kernel datapath (dmesg) for any errors related to OVS or datapath creation.\\n- Correlate timestamps of when ovs-system went DOWN with any recent config changes or service restarts.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- There is a clear anomaly: inter-leaf L2 communication is down while intra-leaf and management appear intact.\\n- The fault is localized to the OVS datapath/bridge layer on the switches (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1). The most likely root cause is that the OVS bridges/datapaths are down or the OVS service is failing, preventing inter-switch L2 forwarding.\\n\\nIf you want, I can run targeted commands next (systemctl status for OVS services, ovs-vsctl show, or ping the controller 20.0.0.100) to collect the specific service/bridge state and logs., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='52881b08-9482-4c79-9865-d4be822f80e2'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
